---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
---

<Layout title="NetP — Network Protocol">
  <h1>NetP — Network Protocol</h1>
  <p style="font-size: 1.05rem; color: var(--color-muted);">
    A standard protocol for describing social network datasets.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Pre-release.</strong> Target submission of the companion paper to <em>Network Science</em>:
    August–September 2026.
  </div>

  <h2>What this is</h2>
  <p>
    The Network Protocol (NetP) is a structured template for describing the social network
    datasets used in empirical articles. Filled along with a publication, it provides a
    complete description of the network, the data collection process, the nodes, the ties,
    and the basic network statistics — at a glance. The goal is to make network research
    more transparent, more replicable, and more comparable across studies.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <a href={base + "/fill"}>Fill the protocol</a> using the structured form on this site.
      The form is driven by a JSON Schema (the single source of truth for the protocol),
      validates your input as you go, and saves your draft locally.
    </li>
    <li>
      Download the filled protocol as JSON. (Markdown and PDF export coming soon.)
    </li>
    <li>
      Include the filled protocol as an appendix to your article, or deposit it alongside
      your dataset in a public repository.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>What the protocol covers</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Overview</strong> — data type, mode, number of waves and relationships, dates, geographic location, associated publication.</li>
    <li><strong>Data collection</strong> — source of the data, details about the source, collection method.</li>
    <li><strong>Nodes</strong> — typology, boundary, exclusions, transformations (per mode).</li>
    <li><strong>Ties</strong> — typology, direction, weights, transformations, name generators (per relationship).</li>
    <li><strong>Statistics</strong> — size, density, average degree, clustering, centralization, reciprocity, longitudinal change (per relationship × wave).</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Worked examples</h2>
  <p>
    Browse <a href={base + "/examples"}>filled protocols</a> for several published datasets,
    or open one directly in the form.
  </p>

  <h2>Roadmap</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>v1 (paper-time, mid-2026): form + JSON/MD/PDF download + in-browser network statistics from uploaded edgelist.</li>
    <li>v2 (post-paper): a backend repository that accepts submitted protocols and exposes search and comparison across datasets — so researchers can ask <em>what is a normal density / centralization / reciprocity for a network of this kind?</em></li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
